# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: io-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:io-language/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:io-language/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:io-language/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:io-language/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:io-language/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:io-language/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:io-language/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:io-language/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:io-language/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:io-language/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:io-language/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:io-language/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:io-language/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:io-language/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:io-language/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:io-language/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:io-language/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:io-language/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:io-language/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:io-language/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:io-language/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:io-language/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:io-language/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:io-language/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:io-language/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:io-language/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:io-language/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:io-language/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:io-language/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:io-language/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:io-language/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:io-language/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:io-language/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:io-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:io-language/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:io-language/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:io-language/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:io-language/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:io-language/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:io-language/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:io-language/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:io-language/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:io-language/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:io-language/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:io-language/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:io-language/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:io-language/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:io-language/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:io-language/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:io-language/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:io-language/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:io-language/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:io-language/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:io-language/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:io-language/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:io-language/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:io-language/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:io-language/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:io-language/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:io-language/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:io-language/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:io-language/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:io-language/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:io-language/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:io-language/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:io-language/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:io-language/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:io-language/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:io-language/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:io-language/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:io-language/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:io-language/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:io-language/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:io-language/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:io-language/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:io-language/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:io-language/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:io-language/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:io-language/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:io-language/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:io-language/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:io-language/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:io-language/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:io-language/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:io-language/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:io-language/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:io-language/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:io-language/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:io-language/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:io-language/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:io-language/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:io-language/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:io-language/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:io-language/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:io-language/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:io-language/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:io-language/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:io-language/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:io-language/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:io-language/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
