[src:io-language/duck-typing] In computer programming, **duck typing** is an application of the duck test—"If it walks like a duck and it quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck"—to determine whether an object can be used for a particular purpose.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] With nominative typing, an object is of a given type if it is declared as such (or if a type's association with the object is inferred through mechanisms such as object inheritance).
[src:io-language/duck-typing] With duck typing, an object is of a given type if it has all methods and properties required by that type.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] Duck typing may be viewed as a usage-based structural equivalence between a given object and the requirements of a type.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] In some statically typed languages such as Boo and D, class type checking can be specified to occur at runtime rather than at compile time.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] C# can invoke dynamic typing which behaves similar to duck typing, through the keyword `dynamic`.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] Duck typing is similar to, but distinct from, structural typing.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] Structural typing is a static typing system that determines type compatibility and equivalence by a type's structure, whereas duck typing is dynamic and determines type compatibility by only that part of a type's structure that is accessed during runtime.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] The TypeScript, Elm and Python languages support structural typing to varying degrees.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] Protocols and interfaces provide a way to explicitly declare that some methods, operators or behaviors must be defined.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] If a third-party library implements a class that cannot be modified, a client cannot use an instance of it with an interface unknown to that library even if the class satisfies the interface requirements.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] A common solution to this problem is the adapter pattern.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] In contrast, with duck typing, the object would be accepted directly without the need for an adapter.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] Template (also called generic) functions or methods apply the duck test in a static typing context; this brings all of the advantages and disadvantages of static versus dynamic type checking.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] Duck typing can also be more flexible in that only the methods actually called at runtime must be implemented, while templates require implementations of all methods that cannot be proven unreachable at compile time.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] In languages such as Java, Scala and Objective-C, reflection may be employed to inspect whether objects implement methods or add necessary methods at runtime.
[src:io-language/duck-typing] For example, Java's MethodHandle API can be used in this manner.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] In computer programming, **homoiconicity** (from the Greek words *homo-* meaning "the same" and *icon* meaning "representation") is an informal property of some programming languages.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] A language is **homoiconic** if a program written in it can be manipulated as data using the language.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The program's internal representation can thus be inferred just by reading the program itself.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] This property is often summarized by saying that the language treats code as data.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The informality of the property arises from the fact that, strictly, this applies to almost all programming languages.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] No consensus exists on a precise definition of the property.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] In a homoiconic language, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] This makes metaprogramming easier than in a language without this property: reflection in the language (examining the program's entities at runtime) depends on a single, homogeneous structure, and it does not have to handle several different structures that would appear in a complex syntax.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Homoiconic languages typically include full support of syntactic macros, allowing the programmer to express transformations of programs in a concise way.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] A commonly cited example is Lisp, which was created to allow for easy list manipulations and where the structure is given by S-expressions that take the form of nested lists, and can be manipulated by other Lisp code.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Other examples are the programming languages Clojure (a contemporary dialect of Lisp), Rebol (also its successor Red), Refal, Prolog, XSLT, and possibly Julia (see the section “Implementation methods” for more details).
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The researchers implicated in this quote might be neurophysiologist and cybernetician Warren Sturgis McCulloch (note the difference in the surname from the note) and philosopher, logician and mathematician Charles Sanders Peirce.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Pierce indeed used the term "icon" in his Semiotic Theory.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] According to Peirce, there are three kinds of sign in communication: the icon, the index and the symbol.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The icon is the simplest representation: an icon physically resembles that which it denotes.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] One advantage of homoiconicity is that extending the language with new concepts typically becomes simpler, as data representing code can be passed between the meta and base layer of the program.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The abstract syntax tree of a function may be composed and manipulated as a data structure in the meta layer, and then evaluated.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] It can be much easier to understand how to manipulate the code since it can be more easily understood as simple data (since the format of the language itself is as a data format).
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] A typical demonstration of homoiconicity is the meta-circular evaluator.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] All Von Neumann architecture systems, which includes the vast majority of general purpose computers today, can implicitly be described as homoiconic due to the way that raw machine code executes in memory, the data type being bytes in memory.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] However, this feature can also be abstracted to the programming language level.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Languages such as Lisp and its dialects, such as Scheme, Clojure, and Racket employ S-expressions to achieve homoiconicity, and are considered the "Purest" forms of homoiconicity, as these languages use the same representation for both data and code.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Other languages provide data structures for easily and efficiently manipulating code.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Notable examples of this weaker form of homoiconicity include Julia, Nim, and Elixir.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Lisp uses S-expressions as an external representation for data and code.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] S-expressions can be read with the primitive Lisp function `READ`.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] `READ` returns Lisp data: lists, symbols, numbers, strings.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The primitive Lisp function `EVAL` uses Lisp code represented as Lisp data, computes side-effects and returns a result.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The result will be printed by the primitive function `PRINT`, which creates an external S-expression from Lisp data.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] Lisp data, a list using different data types: (sub)lists, symbols, strings and integer numbers.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The example uses lists, symbols and numbers.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The operator `:-` separates the head and the body of a clause.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] With `assert/1`* we add it to the existing clauses (add it to the "database"), so we can call it later.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] In other languages we would call it "creating a function during runtime".
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] We can also remove clauses from the database with `abolish/1`, or `retract/1`.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] `call` is analogous to Lisp's `eval` function.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The concept of treating code as data and the manipulation and evaluation thereof can be demonstrated very neatly in Rebol.
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] (Rebol, unlike Lisp, does not require parentheses to separate expressions).
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] (`repeat` is in fact a built-in function in Rebol and is not a language construct or keyword).
[src:io-language/homoiconicity] The block can still be interpreted by using the `do` function provided in Rebol (similar to `eval` in Lisp).
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Remarkable features of Io are its minimal size and openness to using external code resources.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Io is executed by a small, portable virtual machine.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] The language was created by Steve Dekorte in 2002, after trying to help a friend, Dru Nelson, with his language, Cel.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] He learned that he really didn't know much about how languages worked, and set out to write a tiny language to understand the problems better.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Io's goal is to explore conceptual unification and dynamic languages, so the tradeoffs tend to favor simplicity and flexibility over performance.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Assuming the above doStuff is a method, it is being called with zero arguments and as a result, explicit parentheses are not required.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Io is a message passing language, and since everything in Io is a message (excluding comments), each message is sent to a receiver.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] The above example demonstrates this well, but not fully.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] The above example demonstrates message passing in Io; the "version" message is sent to the "System" object.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Operators are a special case where the syntax is not as cut-and-dried as the above examples.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] The Io parser intercepts a set of operators defined by the interpreter, and translates them to method calls.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] All operators in Io are methods; the fact that they do not require explicit parentheses is a convenience.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] As you can see, there is also a little bit of operator precedence happening here, and the precedence levels are the same as with the C precedence levels.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] In Io there are two ways of creating anonymous functions: methods and blocks.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Between them, they are almost identical except for scope.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] While blocks have lexical scope, methods have dynamic scope.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Both *method* and *block* are higher-order functions.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] New objects are created by cloning objects.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] In Io specifically, a new, empty object is created and only the differences between it and its parent are stored within the new object; this behavior is known as differential inheritance.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] Because assignment of `res * i` to `res` is the last action taken, the function implicitly returns the result and so an explicit return expression is not needed.
[src:io-language/io-programming-language] The above demonstrates the usage of ranges, and doesn't use a `for()` loop, which would be faster.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:io-language/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:io-language/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:io-language/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:io-language/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:io-language/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:io-language/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:io-language/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:io-language/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:io-language/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:io-language/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:io-language/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:io-language/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:io-language/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:io-language/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:io-language/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:io-language/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:io-language/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:io-language/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:io-language/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:io-language/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:io-language/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:io-language/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:io-language/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:io-language/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:io-language/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:io-language/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:io-language/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:io-language/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:io-language/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:io-language/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Prototype-based programming uses the process generalized objects, which can then be cloned and extended.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Using fruit as an example, a "fruit" object would represent the properties and functionality of fruit in general.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] A "banana" object would be cloned from the "fruit" object and general properties specific to bananas would be appended.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Each individual "banana" object would be cloned from the generic "banana" object.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Compare to the class-based paradigm, where a "fruit" *class* would be extended by a "banana" *class*.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] The first prototype-based programming language was Daniel G.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Other early prototype systems include Director a.k.a.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Ani (on top of MacLisp) (1976-1979), and contemporaneously and not independently, ThingLab (on top of Smalltalk) (1977-1981), respective PhD projects by Kenneth Michael Kahn at MIT and Alan Hamilton Borning at Stanford (but working with Alan Kay at Xerox PARC).
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Hewitt's Actors team at MIT added support for Prototype OO to ACT-1 in 1979 based on Kahn's work, calling the underlying mechanism "delegation" to distinguish it from the Class OO support they also added as "inheritance".
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Borning popularized the word "prototype" in this context in his 1981 paper in *ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems (TOPLAS)*.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Meanwhile, Rees and Adams's implemented class-less OO using lexical closures in Yale T Scheme (1981-1989)—they didn't say "prototype", but it was isomorphic.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Ken Dickey later published their OO model as portable Scheme code in 1992 as YASOS.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Now, the language that made the name and notion of prototypes popular among academics was Self (1985-1995), developed by David Ungar and Randall Smith.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] But the language that made prototypes ubiquitous for everyone was Brendan Eich's JavaScript (1995-ongoing).
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Since the late 1990s, the classless paradigm has grown increasingly popular.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Some current prototype-oriented languages are JavaScript (and other ECMAScript implementations such as JScript and Flash's ActionScript 1.0), Lua, Cecil, NewtonScript, Io, Ioke, MOO, REBOL and AHK.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Both languages are used to define large distributed software configurations (Jsonnet being directly inspired by GCL, the Google Configuration Language, with which Google defines all its deployments, and has similar semantics though with dynamic binding of variables).
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Since then, other languages like Gerbil Scheme have implemented pure functional lazy prototype systems based on similar principles.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Etymologically, a "prototype" means "first cast" ("cast" in the sense of being manufactured).
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] A prototype is a concrete thing, from which other objects can be created by copying and modifying.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] For example, the International Prototype of the Kilogram is an actual object that really exists, from which new kilogram-objects can be created by copying.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] In comparison, a "class" is an abstract thing, in which objects can belong.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] For example, all kilogram-objects are in the class of KilogramObject, which might be a subclass of MetricObject, and so on.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Advocates of prototype-based programming argue that it encourages the programmer to focus on the behavior of some set of examples and only later worry about classifying these objects into archetypal objects that are later used in a fashion similar to classes.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Almost all prototype-based systems are based on interpreted and dynamically typed languages.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Systems based on statically typed languages are technically feasible, however.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] In prototype-based languages there are no explicit classes.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Objects inherit directly from other objects through a prototype property.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] The prototype property is called `prototype` in Self and JavaScript, or `proto` in Io.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] There are two methods of constructing new objects: *ex nihilo* ("from nothing") object creation or through *cloning* an existing object.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] The former is supported through some form of object literal, declarations where objects can be defined at runtime through special syntax such as `{...}` and passed directly to a variable.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] While most systems support a variety of cloning, *ex nihilo* object creation is not as prominent.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] In class-based languages, a new instance is constructed through a class's constructor function, a special function that reserves a block of memory for the object's members (properties and methods) and returns a reference to that block.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] An optional set of constructor arguments can be passed to the function and are usually held in properties.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] The resulting instance will inherit all the methods and properties that were defined in the class, which acts as a kind of template from which similarly typed objects can be constructed.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Systems that support *ex nihilo* object creation allow new objects to be created from scratch without cloning from an existing prototype.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Such systems provide a special syntax for specifying the properties and behaviors of new objects without referencing existing objects.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] In many prototype languages there exists a root object, often called *Object*, which is set as the default prototype for all other objects created in run-time and which carries commonly needed methods such as a `toString()` function to return a description of the object as a string.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] One useful aspect of *ex nihilo* object creation is to ensure that a new object's slot (properties and methods) names do not have namespace conflicts with the top-level *Object* object.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] (In the JavaScript language, one can do this by using a null prototype, i.e.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] In prototype-based languages that use *delegation*, the language runtime is capable of dispatching the correct method or finding the right piece of data simply by following a series of delegation pointers (from object to its prototype) until a match is found.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] All that is required to establish this behavior-sharing between objects is the delegation pointer.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Unlike the relationship between class and instance in class-based object-oriented languages, the relationship between the prototype and its offshoots does not require that the child object have a memory or structural similarity to the prototype beyond this link.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] As such, the child object can continue to be modified and amended over time without rearranging the structure of its associated prototype as in class-based systems.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] It is also important to note that not only data, but also methods can be added or changed.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] For this reason, some prototype-based languages refer to both data and methods as "slots" or "members".
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] In *concatenative* prototyping - the approach implemented by the Kevo programming language - there are no visible pointers or links to the original prototype from which an object is cloned.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] The prototype (parent) object is copied rather than linked to and there is no delegation.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] As a result, changes to the prototype will not be reflected in cloned objects.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Incidentally, the Cosmos programming language achieves the same through the use of persistent data structures.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] The main conceptual difference under this arrangement is that changes made to a prototype object are not automatically propagated to clones.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] This may be seen as an advantage or disadvantage.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] More sophisticated implementations can avoid this problem, however, although trade-offs between speed and memory are required.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] For example, systems with concatenative prototyping can use a copy-on-write implementation to allow for behind-the-scenes data sharing — and such an approach is indeed followed by Kevo.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Conversely, systems with delegation-based prototyping can use caching to speed up data lookup.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Advocates of class-based object models who criticize prototype-based systems often have concerns similar to the concerns that proponents of static type systems for programming languages have of dynamic type systems (see datatype).
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Usually, such concerns involve correctness, safety, predictability, efficiency and programmer unfamiliarity.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] On the first three points, classes are often seen as analogous to types (in most statically typed object-oriented languages they serve that role) and are proposed to provide contractual guarantees to their instances, and to users of their instances, that they will behave in some given fashion.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] Regarding efficiency, declaring classes simplifies many compiler optimizations that allow developing efficient method and instance-variable lookup.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] For the Self language, much development time was spent on developing, compiling, and interpreting techniques to improve the performance of prototype-based systems versus class-based systems.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] A common criticism made against prototype-based languages is that the community of software developers is unfamiliar with them, despite the popularity and market permeation of JavaScript.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] However, knowledge about prototype-based systems is increasing with the proliferation of JavaScript frameworks and the complex use of JavaScript as the World Wide Web (Web) matures.
[src:io-language/prototype-based-programming] ECMAScript 6 introduced classes as syntactic sugar over JavaScript's existing prototype-based inheritance, providing an alternative way to create objects and manage inheritance.
